<div class="subtitle" id="Intro">Introduction</div>
<p><strong>PHP</strong> is designed to generate web pages interactively on a <strong>web server</strong>.</p>

<br><br>

<script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "ca-pub-4716428189734495";
/* bogo_LargeRectangle_336_280 */
google_ad_slot = "2712696561";
google_ad_width = 336;
google_ad_height = 280;
//-->
</script>
<script type="text/javascript"
src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script>

<br><br>
<p>Unlike HTML, where the web browser uses tags and markup to generate a page, PHP code runs between the <strong>requested page</strong> and the <strong>web server</strong>. </p>
<p>While PHP is great for web application development, it doesn't store information by itself. Because of that, we need a database, <strong>MySQL</strong>. PHP and MySql have been developed with each other in mind. The programming interfaces between them are logically paired up.</p>



<p>The current release of MySQL is the 5.x version. MySQL 5.6 provides performance that is comparable to other databases such as Oracle, Informix, DB2 (IBM), and SQL Server (Microsoft).</p>
<p><strong>Apache</strong> is a web server and has two major versions in use today: 1.3 and 2. Apache 2 is a major rewrite and supports <strong>threading</strong> though PHP isn't totally ready yet. </p>
<br />

<br />

